Pour the @water{300%ml} for the rice into a #saucepan and bring to the boil. When
boiling, add the @vegetable stock powder{1} and @ground turmeric{1}, stir in the
@basmati rice{150%g}, lower the heat to medium and pop a #lid on the pan. Leave
to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and
leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice
will continue to cook in its own steam).

Halve the @green pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Slice into thin strips.
Trim the @green beans{150%g} then chop into thirds. Trim and grate the @carrot{1}.
Trim the @spring onion{1} then slice thinly. Roughly chop the @coriander{1}(stalks
and all). Peel and grate the @ginger{1/2}. Zest and quarter the @lime{1/2}.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan on medium high heat. Once hot,
add the green pepper and green beans, fry until softened, ~{4-6%minutes}. Add the
@ketjap manis{25%ml}, @soy sauce{25%ml}, @Kuala Lumpur style curry powder{1} and
ginger. Let it bubble for ~{1-2%minutes}.

> TIP: Use less Kuala Lumpur spice if you don't like it too spicy.

Meanwhile, roughly chop the @salted peanuts{25%g}. Once the rice is cooked, add it
to the pan with the veg. Once thoroughly mixed add the carrot and lime zest and
heat through for ~{1-2%minutes}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{} to taste.

Serve the rice in #bowls{}, cover with #foil to keep warm and wipe out the pan.
Return to a high heat and add a drizzle of @oil{}. Crack your @eggs{2} into the
pan and fry until the white of the egg is opaque and the yolk still has a wobble,
~{4-5%minutes}.

> TIP: Cook for a couple more minutes if you prefer your yolk a little more cooked.

Top each bowl of rice with a fried egg, sprinkle on the spring onion, coriander
and the chopped peanuts. Serve with a wedge of lime for squeezing over. Enjoy!